i== The Agrestic ==		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iWhile sitting at a Denny's in Greenwood, Indiana, staring down at		gopher.black	70
ia paper place-mat featuring "Guess Who?", I had this conversation		gopher.black	70
iwith my friend Josh. There was much coffee involved, and probably		gopher.black	70
ia burger in there somewhere, and we were more certainly awake far		gopher.black	70
itoo late in the night. My argument stated, I continued for him as		gopher.black	70
iI will for you now.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iThe future is over. It's been done, you see. 1985! We're well		gopher.black	70
ipassed that, even if it was a fictional version of it. If this		gopher.black	70
itime is no longer the future, or even "A" future, what is it? We		gopher.black	70
ihave generational terms, decade terms, and occasionally history		gopher.black	70
igrants a time with an overall label in retrospect. These are all		gopher.black	70
iscientific, calculated, or reactive. They don't attempt to		gopher.black	70
idescribe us while we are still in the act of being. They describe		gopher.black	70
ithe past, or they describe the calendar of the present.		gopher.black	70
iUncertainty clouds the present and the days ahead and puts us back		gopher.black	70
iinto nonsense-words again, right? 		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iWhat if we chose a nonsense word for the times we're in and the		gopher.black	70
itimes to come that wasn't bland or neutral, but instead one that		gopher.black	70
ievoked in us a primal sense of experience. Imagine that a word		gopher.black	70
icould convey in existential, individual, human terms a sense of		gopher.black	70
ithe entire days to come. It wouldn't need to be packed with		gopher.black	70
icontext from other sources but contain them within its full		gopher.black	70
iunderstanding.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iAgrestic.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iThat is the "future" I envision and put forth in my own mind and		gopher.black	70
iin my interactions with the world. It can be summed up as the		gopher.black	70
ilogical conclusion to the phrase:		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
i"Then they all decided the internet was a pretty bad idea."		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iWhat happens next. What do we find. Rustic. Beauty. The Earth.		gopher.black	70
iHuman animals in the dirt, in the trees, in the seas. Unpack as		gopher.black	70
imuch as you can from the word and from its idea and from all that		gopher.black	70
icame before it and let it saturate you.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iIs it silly, is it absurd, is it infinitely unlikely to happen?		gopher.black	70
iWho cares? Flying cars are EXACTLY as absurd.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iHere's the key to the whole thing: whatever you aim at you're not		gopher.black	70
igoing to hit, but you're going to end up close. If you aim at		gopher.black	70
iflying cars and nuclear war... I don't want to go there with you.		gopher.black	70
iIf you aim at a world where we found peace with our planet and		gopher.black	70
ididn't let our creations define us then everyone deserves some		gopher.black	70
igod-damned high fives in my book.		gopher.black	70
i		gopher.black	70
iAgrestic. Say it with me. It may not be a word (it really, really		gopher.black	70
iis a word), but that doesn't matter. It's in your head and it's in		gopher.black	70
imy head and it's more fucking real than a flux capacitor.		gopher.black	70
